{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d1a8df72-3234-4cab-acf9-86e261bac9c0","content":"In .NET MAUI, the recommended approach is to use **Window lifecycle events** instead of the `Application`-level overrides.\n\nCreate a custom `Window` subclass and override the lifecycle methods:\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()      // ← replaces OnStart\n    {\n        base.OnCreated();\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnDeactivated()  // ← replaces OnSleep\n    {\n        base.OnDeactivated();\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnResumed()      // ← replaces OnResume\n    {\n        base.OnResumed();\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThen in your `App` class:\n\n```csharp\npublic class App : Application\n{\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n        => new MyWindow(new MainPage());\n}\n```\n\n**Quick mapping:**\n| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `OnCreated()` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `OnDeactivated()` / `OnStopped()` |\n| `OnResume()` | `OnResumed()` / `OnActivated()` |\n\n`OnStopped()` fires when the app goes fully to the background; `OnDeactivated()` fires when it just loses focus. Use whichever matches your original intent.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"53517c86-9416-4010-a233-26b33bfa6754","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI, specifically about the Application lifecycle methods (OnStart, OnSleep, OnResume). Let me provide the answer from my knowledge.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` in your `Application` class.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. You use the `Window` lifecycle events or the cross-platform lifecycle events through the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`. However, the `Application` class in MAUI still has `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` virtual methods that you can override — they weren't removed.\n\n\nActually, I need to correct myself — the `Application` class in .NET MAUI doesn't expose `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` as overridable methods the way Xamarin.Forms did. Instead, MAUI shifted to a `Window`-based lifecycle model where you override `CreateWindow()` in your `Application` class to handle lifecycle events.\n\nThe `Window` class provides methods like `OnCreated`, `OnActivated`, `OnDeactivated`, `OnStopped`, `OnResumed`, and `OnDestroying` for managing the app's lifecycle stages. I'm mapping out how the old Xamarin.Forms lifecycle methods translate to MAUI's Window-based approach, so I can show the user the direct equivalents and give them a practical code example to work with.","outputTokens":1264,"requestId":"0838:162674:A5913D:BF809D:69F2A8AE"},"id":"ea84505b-2969-43f5-bd8c-493751234da6","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:56:35.483Z","parentId":"825a5bdf-7adf-4277-ba34-ebf157cf5273"}
